n organizations, labor struggles, and political culture with news, strategies, education, and mutual aid. Mapping the emancipation circuits, Davis shows the geography of ideas of freedom---circulating on shipping routes, via army maneuvers, and with itinerant activists---that became the basis for the first mass Black political movement for equal citizenship in the United States. In this work, she reconfigures understandings of the evolution of southern Black political agendas while outlining the origins of the enduring Black freedom struggle from the Jim Crow era to the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryy1863-1877. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and governmenty19th century. 0aFreed personsxPolitical activityzSouthern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aFreedmenxPolitical activityzSouthern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aReconstruction (U.S. history, 1865-1877). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022 Englishz978311099455108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022z9783110994520oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478022800?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022800423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022800/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978